description: From Middle English superceden, from Middle French superceder, from Latin supersedēre: super- (“over-”) + sedēre (“to sit”).

verbs.description: supercede (third-person singular simple present supercedes, present participle superceding, simple past and past participle superceded)

examples: To it a new species of conveyancing owes its origin, which dispenses with livery of seisin, and almost entirely supercedes, in practice, the employment of common law deeds.
